{"id": "6094f474123b4d92a4d748824af5260d", "timestamp": "2025-12-11 05:54:41", "name": "Scientist0", "content": "Thought: The proposed topic aligns strongly with the team's evolving research trajectory, building on prior discussions about dynamic adaptation in efficient fine-tuning. It satisfies all selection criteria: (1) It identifies a clear gap—current adapter modules lack *learned*, *differentiable* mechanisms for input-adaptive capacity control, relying instead on static or heuristic designs; (2) It introduces innovative solutions—soft scaling via hypernetworks, stochastic depth with input-conditioned survival probabilities, and policy-driven structured sparsity—all trainable end-to-end; (3) The topic is well-scoped and original, focusing on differentiable plasticity within adapters rather than broader model compression or routing; (4) It offers measurable impact through new evaluation paradigms like compute efficiency gain (CEG) and Pareto-aware analysis across diverse tasks (e.g., GLUE, VQA), where variable complexity naturally demands adaptive computation. By targeting both performance and efficiency, this direction has high relevance for real-world deployment, especially in multi-task and edge-AI scenarios. Committing now enables rapid prototyping, empirical validation, and iterative refinement—key to advancing from concept to impactful contribution.\n\nTopic: ```json{\"Selected Topic\": \"Learning to Scale: Input-Adaptive Adapter Modules with Differentiable Capacity Control\"}```", "role": "assistant", "url": null, "metadata": null, "_colored_name": "\u001b[90mScientist0\u001b[0m"}
{"id": "d145d4f1c14440e485ad89de858cfdb6", "timestamp": "2025-12-11 05:54:44", "name": "Scientist0", "content": "The selected topic, *\"Learning to Scale: Input-Adaptive Adapter Modules with Differentiable Capacity Control\"*, addresses a key gap in efficient fine-tuning by introducing learnable, end-to-end mechanisms for dynamic capacity adjustment in adapter modules. It proposes innovative methods—such as hypernetwork-generated widths, input-conditioned stochastic depth, and policy-driven sparsity—to enable input-adaptive computation. The approach is well-scoped, original, and targets measurable impact through metrics like compute efficiency gain and Pareto analysis across tasks (e.g., GLUE, VQA). Finalizing the topic now enables immediate prototyping, empirical validation, and accelerated progress toward deployment-relevant solutions in multi-task and edge-AI settings.", "role": "assistant", "url": null, "metadata": null, "_colored_name": "\u001b[90mScientist0\u001b[0m"}
